## Task
Add pipeline timing and a 5-iteration rolling average to `ProcessorManager` in `mothership/internal/signal/processor.go`.

## Changes to ProcessorManager struct (lines 221-228)
Add these fields:
```go
type ProcessorManager struct {
    // ... existing fields ...
    iterDurations [5]time.Duration  // ring buffer for last 5 iteration times
    iterIdx       int               // next write index (mod 5)
    iterCount     int               // how many values filled (0-5)
    shedLevel     int               // current load shedding level (0-3)
    steadyCount   int               // consecutive iters below recovery threshold
}
```

## Changes to LinkProcessor.Process() (line 54)
Wrap the entire Process body to time it. At the START of Process():
```go
t0 := time.Now()
```
At the END of Process(), before return, update the manager's ring buffer. BUT — Process is on LinkProcessor, not ProcessorManager. So instead, add timing to ProcessorManager.Process() (line 252):

```go
func (pm *ProcessorManager) Process(linkID string, ...) (*ProcessResult, error) {
    t0 := time.Now()
    // ... existing lock + delegate to processor ...
    result, err := processor.Process(payload, rssiDBm, nSub, recvTime)
    pm.mu.Unlock()  // already have write lock
    elapsed := time.Since(t0)
    pm.updateShedding(elapsed)
    return result, err
}
```

## New method updateShedding(elapsed time.Duration)
```go
func (pm *ProcessorManager) updateShedding(elapsed time.Duration) {
    pm.iterDurations[pm.iterIdx%5] = elapsed
    pm.iterIdx++
    if pm.iterCount < 5 { pm.iterCount++ }

    // compute rolling avg
    var sum time.Duration
    for i := 0; i < pm.iterCount; i++ {
        sum += pm.iterDurations[i]
    }
    avg := sum / time.Duration(pm.iterCount)

    // level up
    if avg >= 95*time.Millisecond && pm.shedLevel < 3 {
        pm.shedLevel = 3; pm.steadyCount = 0
    } else if avg >= 90*time.Millisecond && pm.shedLevel < 2 {
        pm.shedLevel = 2; pm.steadyCount = 0
    } else if avg >= 80*time.Millisecond && pm.shedLevel < 1 {
        pm.shedLevel = 1; pm.steadyCount = 0
    }

    // recovery: step down one level when avg < 60ms for 10 consecutive iters
    if avg < 60*time.Millisecond {
        pm.steadyCount++
        if pm.steadyCount >= 10 && pm.shedLevel > 0 {
            pm.shedLevel--
            pm.steadyCount = 0
        }
    } else {
        pm.steadyCount = 0
    }
}
```

## New getter
```go
func (pm *ProcessorManager) GetShedLevel() int {
    pm.mu.RLock()
    defer pm.mu.RUnlock()
    return pm.shedLevel
}
```

Note: `updateShedding` must NOT hold `pm.mu` because it's called after unlock. The iterDurations ring buffer is only written from `Process` so it is already serialized by the caller's lock sequence. Add a separate `mu` for the shed state or call updateShedding while still holding pm.mu — simplest: call it BEFORE Unlock, while still holding the write lock.

